<DOC><DOCNO> AP890228-0039 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-28-89 0618EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     02-28 0542</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0558</SECOND><HEAD>Rain, Snow Continue in Southeast</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Snow fell in parts of the Appalachians early today and heavyrains soaked Alabama, flooding some roads.   The heaviest snow accumulations were in the Blue Ridge Mountainsof Virginia and North Carolina and in north central Tennessee, whereup to 8 inches fell.   Snow also fell from North Dakota to Wisconsin, with 2 inchesrecorded at Minneapolis and 4 inches on the ground at Little Falls,Minn.   Showers and thunderstorms extended from central Louisiana acrossthe Tennessee Valley into North Carolina, where more than 1\ inchesof rain fell in Rowan County.   Heavy rains flooded some roads in Morgan County, Ala., and aflash flood watch remained in effect from the west central to thenortheast part of the state.   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 1 a.m. ESTincluded nearly 1} inches at Columbus, Miss., Air Force Base and1.36 inches at Tuscaloosa, Ala.   Temperatures early this morning were in the single digits andteens over the northern Rockies, the northern Plains, the upperMississippi Valley, the upper Great Lakes and New England.   Temperatures were in the 50s and 60s over the Gulf Coast region,Florida, the southern Atlantic Coast, Southern California andsouthwest Arizona.   Today's forecast called for snow over the northern Rockies, thenorthern Plains, and much of the Great Lakes and Ohio Valley.Showers and some thunderstorms were expected to prevail from thelower Mississippi Valley to the Carolinas and the middle Atlanticstates, and over the Pacific Northwest. Fair to partly sunny skieswere forecast across much of the rest of the nation.   High temperatures were to remain in the single digits and teensfrom the northern Rockies across North Dakota and the upperMississippi Valley to western Upper Michigan; in the 20s and 30s inthe northern Plateau, across South Dakota and the central Plains,much of the middle Mississippi Valley, the Great Lakes, the OhioValley and the northern Pacific Coast; in the 60s and 70s fromcentral and Southern California across the southern Plateau, thesouthern Rockies, much of southern Texas, the Gulf Coast region,Florida and the southern Atlantic Coast; and in the 80s over theDesert Southwest and south central Texas. Much of the remainder ofthe nation was to have highs in the 40s and 50s.   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 5degrees below zero at Marquette, Mich., to 74 degrees at Key West,Fla.   Other reports:   _East: Atlanta 48 rain; Boston 28 fair; Buffalo 19 snow;Charleston, S.C., 62 cloudy; Cincinnati 26 foggy; Cleveland 22cloudy; Detroit 21 partly cloudy; Miami 70 cloudy; New York 29 fair;Philadelphia 31 fair; Pittsburgh 18 foggy; Portland, Maine, 16 fair;Washington 37 cloudy.   _Central: Bismarck 8 snow; Chicago 19 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 44cloudy; Denver 28 snow; Des Moines 24 fair; Indianapolis 23 fair;Kansas City 30 cloudy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 14 snow; Nashville 31partly cloudy; New Orleans 67 partly cloudy; St. Louis 28 fair.   _West: Albuquerque 33 fair; Anchorage 22 fair; Las Vegas 53 fair;Los Angeles 55 foggy; Phoenix 64 fair; Salt Lake City 36 cloudy; SanDiego 57 cloudy; San Francisco 47 windy;   _Canada: Montreal 16 fair; Toronto 5 fair.</TEXT></DOC>